    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1974-11-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1974-11-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="86"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d86">
                <head>86. Note From the United States to the Soviet Union<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d86fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss target="#t_RG_1"
                            >RG</gloss> 59, Records of the Office of the Counselor, Lot File 81D286,
                        Box 6, <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss>, November–December 1977. No
                        classification marking. A covering memorandum from <persName
                            corresp="#p_SH_2">Sonnenfeldt</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_HWG_1">Hyland</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1"
                            >Kissinger</persName> explains that the note was to be passed to
                            <persName corresp="#p_DAF_1">Dobrynin</persName> and that it had
                        incorporated the changes in paragraph 5 that <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1"
                            >Kissinger</persName> had requested. (Ibid.) <persName
                            corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName> gave <persName
                            corresp="#p_DAF_1">Dobrynin</persName> the note on November 13. (Ford
                        Library, National Security Adviser, <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1"
                            >Kissinger</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_SBA_1">Scowcroft</persName>
                        West Wing Office Files, Box 27, <gloss target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss>, The
                        “D” File)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content" calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1974-11-13">undated</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1. Beginning in October 1977, and for the period through January 1, 1984, the
                    number of <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss> launchers, <gloss
                        target="#t_SLBM_1">SLBM</gloss> launchers, and heavy strategic bombers will
                    be limited as follows: for the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> no more than
                    2200; for the <gloss target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss> no more than 2400.</p>
                <p>2. Thereafter, in the period lasting through the end of the new agreement
                    (December 31, 1985), the number of weapons specified in paragraph 1 will be no
                    more than 2400 for the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> and for the <gloss
                        target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss>, unless agreement is reached beforehand on
                    additional mutual reductions.</p>
                <p>3. During the period from October 1977 through January 1, 1984, the number of
                    ICBMs and SLBMs equipped with MIRVs will be limited as follows: for the <gloss
                        target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> no more than 1320 and for the <gloss
                        target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss> no more than 1120.</p>
                <pb facs="0409" n="380" xml:id="pg_380"/>
                <p>4. Thereafter, in the period lasting through the end of the new agreement
                    (December 31, 1985), the limits on the number of ICBMs and SLBMs equipped with
                    MIRVs will be 1320 for both the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> and the
                        <gloss target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss>.</p>
                <p>5. During the period of a new agreement, from October 1977 through December 1985,
                    both the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> and the <gloss target="#t_USSR_1"
                        >USSR</gloss> will have the right to deploy (a) no more than 250 new heavy
                    strategic bombers, (b) no more than 288 modern SLBMs on new types of modern
                    ballistic missile submarines, (c) no more than 180 new, modern large ICBMs
                    equipped with MIRVs.</p>
                <p>6. By the beginning of 1984, at the latest, the <gloss target="#t_US_1"
                        >US</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss> will resume
                    negotiations on a further agreement limiting strategic arms, with the aim of
                    agreeing on a program of phased reductions to take effect after 1985.</p>
            </div>
